          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":50,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"sunday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"18–20 km at easy pace (5:24–6:11/km). Keep effort conversational — this is aerobic base, not a test. Your Achilles history means a gradual warm-up matters here, so start at the slower end of easy pace for the first 2 km.\"},\"monday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. After Sunday's long run, passive recovery lets the adaptation happen. Think of today as part of the training, not a gap in it.\"},\"tuesday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"10 km easy (5:24–6:11/km). Legs may still feel Sunday's effort — that's normal. Run by feel and stay honest with your pace. No need to prove anything today.\"},\"wednesday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"10 km total with 20 min at threshold pace (4:29/km). Warm up 2–3 km easy, hold threshold for 20 min, cool down easy. This session maintains your lactate-clearance fitness without overloading mid-week.\"},\"thursday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"8 km easy (5:24–6:11/km). A light aerobic top-up to keep your weekly volume on track. Stay fully in your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone — no tempo creep.\"},\"friday\":{\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"30–45 min low-impact cross-training (cycling, swimming, or yoga). This keeps your aerobic engine ticking without additional impact stress on your left Achilles. A good day to check in with how that tendon is feeling.\"},\"saturday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"10 km easy (5:24–6:11/km). Shake-out before tomorrow's long run. Flat route preferred, relaxed effort. Consider this a tune-up, not a training stimulus.\"},\"week_summary\":\"Welcome back, Maria — and well done on a strong training block heading into this maintenance phase. Your recent history shows consistent 62–64 km weeks with solid long runs, and the slight dip to 47 km in the most recent week actually sets us up nicely here. This first week targets 50 km, giving your body a gentle reset before we settle into a sustainable maintenance rhythm. The structure follows an 80/20 split: the large majority of your running stays in your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone, with one quality session mid-week to keep your threshold fitness sharp. Your pace-zone index of 46.7 reflects genuine marathon-level fitness, and the goal this phase is simply to protect and maintain that — not chase new adaptations. One thing worth keeping in mind: with your Achilles history, easy really does mean easy on those aerobic runs. If anything feels off in that left tendon at any point, let's talk before adjusting on your own.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
